post_text:
Look at the amazing innovation from Jen Kiekhoefer over at Fairview as she completes her Sensory Pathway. Jen received a grant from the Plymouth Education Foundation in the amount of $2100 this year.

Jen wanted to create a sensory hallway for students who need to take a break and have a safe space to constructively channel extra energy. This will in turn help them return to their studies with renewed concentration.

The PEF loves supporting these awesome ideas and seeing Grants in Action. Way to go, Jen!!

post_text:
The Foundation is built around giving back, and scholarship season is one of our very favorites. We work with donors who want to make an investment in PHS graduates and their futures. Today, we are honoring our donors who have helped shape lives, and a few scholarship winners who are doing the same.

Claire Wichert is a 2015 PHS graduate. She graduated from Edgewood College in 2019, and is now a labor and delivery nurse at Oconomowoc Memorial Hospital. Elise Suttner is also a 2015 PHS graduate. She went on to graduate from University of Madison in 2019, and is now a nurse on the oncology unit at the University of Colorado Hospital.

Plymouth community, help me in thanking these two brave young women who are working on the front line everyday. They are Plymouth Strong and they are making a difference!

post_text:
Good morning!

Missing school? How about a history lesson about how the Plymouth Education Foundation began!

In 1978, a Plymouth teacher and her husband, having no children, left a significant gift in trust to benefit Plymouth students with opportunities not included in the school district's budget such as the annual middle school trip to Camp Anokijig. The funds were held in trust for 10 years and in July 1988, the School Board decided to use this generous gift to create the Plymouth Education Foundation, which is a 501(c)3 non-profit organization whose purpose is to enhance the educational experience of students in the Plymouth School District. The Plymouth Education Foundation celebrates its more than 30 years of leading support for innovative initiatives that prepare all students to succeed in life and make a difference in society.

We are so proud of the 30 plus years of supporting the Plymouth School District!

Happy National Peanut Butter & Jelly Day!

Did you know that the "original" recipe for a simple peanut butter and jelly sandwich can be traced back to 1901. PB & J is still popular today. The average American child will consumer 1,500 PB & J sandwiches by the time they graduate high school. Who is having a PB & J sandwich for lunch today? Share a picture of your PB & J creation with us.

CLASS OF 1979...it's time for your 40th reunion!!!

Plymouth Panther Boys Basketball
November 13, 2017 at 8:43 PM ¬∑

Let's hear it for 1990! What your favorite memories from that year?
--------- 1990 ------------
* World Changing Event: Solitaire was originally included in early computer programs to help users strengthen their clicking and dragging skills.

* The Top Song was Because I Love You (The Postman Song) Stevie B

post_text:
You can have May flowers all year long...if you purchase a flower card from Cain's Bridal Wreath annual fundraising benefit. This year the sale of the $20.00 card will benefit the Plymouth Education Foundation.

If you are not familiar with the Flower Card promotion, this is how it works. Your $20 purchase "buys" you a monthly visit to Cain's Bridal Wreath to pick up a fresh bouquet of flowers. Your card will be punched each month when you visit beginning in June 2017, and $10 out of your $20 donation will be donated to the Plymouth Education Foundation to be used for the group's annual grant awards to education programs throughout the Plymouth School District.

Cards are available in the District Office at Plymouth High School, at Cain's Bridal Wreath, the Plymouth Chamber of Commerce office, Allechant Boutique, or from Plymouth Education Foundation board members. After your purchase you have until June 2018 to enjoy our fresh flowers every month while supporting the PEF's grant program. For more information contact Andrea Schultz, PEF Executive Director, 920-892-2661 x1008.

post_text:
PHS seeking Alumni Hall of Fame nominees

The Plymouth High School Student Council is accepting nominations for the Alumni Hall of Fame, which honors graduates who have made a difference, achieved a high level of success, and given unselfishly to make their community a better place.

Nominees must have graduated from Plymouth High School at least 10 years ago, and should be people who have made exceptional achievements in endeavors including, but not limited to, education, science and technology, business, literature, athletics, and public service.

Nominations are due Monday, May 15. The Student Council Hall of Fame Committee chooses the inductees, which are announced during the PHS graduation ceremony in June and formally inducted during PHS Homecoming in the fall.

The Alumni Hall of Fame was created in 2010 to provide current students and the extended community the opportunity to honor excellence. Inductees serve as role models for students, and offer a chance to celebrate the successes of graduates.

To learn more or obtain a nomination form, visit www.plymouth.k12.wi.us.

post_text:
Public invited to PHS Open House

Families and community members are invited to tour Plymouth High School as part of its 50th anniversary celebration.

An open house will be held from 3:30 to 7 p.m. Thursday, Feb. 23. Visitors can:

Tour the Food Science & Agriculture Center.
Explore the LTC-Plymouth Science & Technology Center.
See examples of student work throughout the building.
View 50 years' worth of posters and programs from PHS student productions.
Sample cookies baked by culinary arts students.
National Honor Society students will be available to greet and guide visitors.

The open house is being held in conjunction with parent-teacher conferences. Teachers will be available in their classrooms for parents who wish to discuss student progress.

Plymouth Comprehensive High School opened for classes Sept. 6, 1966, though some areas were not yet completed until that December. It was designed to offer a broad choice of subjects but also a large amount of individual attention - both of which continue to be hallmarks of the school.

For those who are considering making a year-end charitable contribution to a charity, planning your giving to the Plymouth Education Foundation may align with your passions and maximize your contributions giving you a tax break in 2015.

The Plymouth Education Foundation is a nonprofit, 501(c)(3), organization dedicated for over 25 years to enhance the educational experience for students in the Plymouth School District.

Your year-end gift can be made online at www.plymouthedfoundation.org.

Thank you for your support!

District staff, students, and community members are invited to a Grants information meeting/Q&A session on November 18 at 6:30 p.m. in the board room at Plymouth High School.

Bring ideas to share, questions, and/or feedback.

Learn more:

post_text: Fairview Student Council presented Plymouth Education Foundation with a check for over $250 raised through a Coins For Kindness school-wide drive to Pay It Forward. The foundation is grateful to Fairview students, staff, and families for helping to enhance the educational experience for current and future students, k-12, in the district. The money raised will help fund $10,000 in new grants the foundation is awarding in May to district staff as well as to district students and community members who partner with district staff. The grants application deadline is February 5, 2016, and can be found at www.plymouthedfoundation.org.

The foundation is grateful to Fairview students, staff, and families for helping to enhance the educational experience for current and future students, k-12, in the district. The money raised will help fund $10,000 in new grants the foundation is awarding in May to district staff as well as to district students and community members who partner with district staff. The grants application deadline is February 5, 2016, and can be found at www.plymouthedfoundation.org.

post_text:
PHS seeking Alumni Hall of Fame nominees

The Plymouth High School Student Council is accepting nominations for the Alumni Hall of Fame, which honors individuals who have made a difference, who have achieved a high level of success, and who have given unselfishly to make their community a better place.

Nominations are due Friday, May 1. Selections will be made by the Student Council Hall of Fame Committee.The 2015 inductees will be announced during the PHS graduation ceremony June 7, with the formal induction taking place Oct. 9 during Homecoming.
